API Knowledge:
java.util.ArrayList.get() is a method used to return the element at the specified position in this list.
java.util.LinkedList.get() is a method used to return the element at the specified position in this list.
The java.util.ArrayList.get() method retrieves the element at the specified index in the list.
The java.util.LinkedList.get() method retrieves the element at the specified position in the list.
Q: Based on the API Knowledge above, do java.util.ArrayList.get() and java.util.LinkedList.get() have similar usage but different behaviors?

API Knowledge:
java.util.Iterator.remove() is used to remove the last element returned by the iterator from the underlying collection.
java.util.ListIterator.add() is used to insert the specified element into the list (optional operation).
The java.util.Iterator.remove() method can only be called once per call to next(). It can be used to remove the last element returned by this iterator.
The java.util.ListIterator.add() method inserts the specified element into the list at the current position of the iterator.
Q: Based on the API Knowledge above, do java.util.Iterator.remove() and java.util.ListIterator.add() have similar usage but different behaviors?

API Knowledge:
java.lang.String.concat() is used to concatenate the specified string to the end of this string.
java.lang.System.arraycopy() is a static method that copies a range of elements from an array into a new destination array.
The java.lang.String.concat() method concatenates the given string to the end of the current string.
The java.lang.System.arraycopy() method is used for copying a subsequence of array components from one array to another.
Q: Based on the API Knowledge above, do java.lang.String.concat() and java.lang.System.arraycopy() have similar usage but different behaviors?

API Knowledge:
java.util.HashMap.put() is used to associate a specific value with a specific key in this map.
java.util.concurrent.ConcurrentHashMap.put() is used to associate a specific value with a specific key in this concurrent hash map.
The java.util.HashMap.put() method allows null values and one null key. It is not thread-safe and may require external synchronization.
The java.util.concurrent.ConcurrentHashMap.put() method does not allow null values or null keys. It is thread-safe and provides better performance in a multi-threading environment.
Q: Based on the API Knowledge above, do java.util.HashMap.put() and java.util.concurrent.ConcurrentHashMap.put() have similar usage but different behaviors?
